Here's how to implement all three in your `EditProductPage`:

**1 & 2. Intercept back navigation and conditionally cancel it:**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` (hardware/gesture back) and handle the Shell toolbar back button:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            ShowUnsavedChangesDialog();
            return true; // cancel navigation
        }
        return base.OnBackButtonPressed();
    }

    private async void ShowUnsavedChangesDialog()
    {
        bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (leave)
        {
            _hasUnsavedChanges = false;
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
        }
    }
}
```

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button:**

In your XAML, hide the default back button and add your own toolbar item:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage"
             Shell.BackButtonBehavior="{StaticResource CancelBackButton}">

    <ContentPage.Resources>
        <BackButtonBehavior x:Key="CancelBackButton"
                            TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </ContentPage.Resources>
</ContentPage>
```

Or set it inline and bind the command in code-behind:

```xml
<Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                        IsVisible="True">
        <BackButtonBehavior.Command>
            <x:NullExtension />
        </BackButtonBehavior.Command>
    </BackButtonBehavior>
</Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
```

```csharp
// In constructor or OnAppearing
Shell.SetBackButtonBehavior(this, new BackButtonBehavior
{
    TextOverride = "Cancel",
    Command = new Command(async () =>
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
            ShowUnsavedChangesDialog();
        else
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    })
});
```

**Key points:**
- `OnBackButtonPressed` handles Android hardware/swipe back — return `true` to cancel.
- `BackButtonBehavior.Command` handles the **Shell toolbar** back button tap.
- You need both to fully guard navigation. The `TextOverride` property replaces the arrow with "Cancel".
